qa_pairs.text_input: What different types of HPV vaccines are licensed for use in the United States?
qa_pairs.output: The three HPV vaccines licensed for use in the United States are: Human Papillomavirus Quadrivalent (Types 6, 11, 16, 18) Vaccine, Recombinant (Gardasil), Human Papillomavirus Bivalent (Types 16 and 18) Vaccine, Recombinant (Cervarix), and Human Papillomavirus 9-valent Vaccine, Recombinant (Gardasil 9).

qa_pairs.text_input: What is the difference between Gardasil and Gardasil 9?
qa_pairs.output: Gardasil protects against 4 types of HPV (6, 11, 16, and 18), while Gardasil 9 protects against 9 types of HPV (6, 11, 16, 18, 31, 33, 45, 52, and 58).

qa_pairs.text_input: Which HPV vaccine is recommended for use in the United States?
qa_pairs.output: The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) recommends that all preteens ages 11 or 12 receive two doses of the HPV vaccine, with the second dose given 6 to 12 months after the first dose. The vaccine can also be given to catch-up vaccination of preteens and young adults through age 26 who have not been vaccinated or have not completed the full series of vaccinations.
